@NODE INTRO "What's a zone editor?"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}What the Hell's a Zone Editor?@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}
    If you've never used zones in @{B}Blitz Basic@{UB}, you'll probably be at a
  loss as to what this does. If you do use them however, you'll know how
  much effort is involved in setting thier limits.
    Zones are essentially a method of marking out and numbering
  areas on screen. Although not very flexible it is @{B}very fast@{UB}, and
  often very useful.
    This program lets you define both rectangular and circular zones
  using a full amiga GUI, saving them to a @{B}simple text file@{UB}.
    
    What this means is, that your own programs can use a simple bit of    
  @{"code" LINK LOAD} to load the text file, and use the data to define the zones.
    Once that simple task is done, any future changes to your zones are
  @{B}simple@{UB}. Just load the editor, redefine the zones and save them again.
          
    And what makes things easier is the lovely @{"features" LINK FEATURES}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUIREMENTS "Can I run this thing?"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}Requirements?@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

    To be honest I've no idea what other systems it runs under, because I
  know no-one else who owns an Amiga.

    I know in theory what it @{i}should @{ui} run under.

  @{fg highlight}Operating Systems@{fg text}
    @{B}OS 3.0@{UB} or above is required for the Intuition the program uses.

  @{fg highlight}Memory@{fg text}
    @{B}2MB Chip RAM@{UB} is plenty for most zone editing. Of course it
  doesn't hurt to have a wad of Fast RAM, but at a push I think this could
  run with just 512KB of Chip RAM.

  @{fg highlight}Processor@{fg text}
    It's a very stable program, but not blindingly fast, as is the way
  of all intuition based programs. Vanilla A1200 users will find this
  sluggish so any processor lower than an 68030 requires patience.
    Works fine and dandy on my '040/40mhz though.

    If it works under a system I haven't mentioned here, or indeed
  if you find any bugs, please write and tell @{"me" LINK ME} about it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "How do I Install this?"
  @{fg highlight}@{B}@{U}Installation@{UU}@{UB}@{fg text}

  Just drag the ZoneED drawer to wherever you want on your harddisk.
    If you want it to run from floppy then format a disk with an
  install bootblock and expand this archive straight into the root of DF0:

  Make sure you install the following libraries, in @{B}LIBS:@{UB}
   @{FG FILL} asl.library
    diskfont.library
    mathtrans.library
    reqtools.library@{FG TEXT}

    These are fairly common, and you should probably own them already.

  After that, you are ready to run.

    To run the ZoneED Either:-

    @{I}* Double click on the Workbench Icon
    * Go the the appropriate CLI drawer and type ZoneED@{UI}

@ENDNODE

