@NODE ZNE "The .ZNE file format"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}Using the .ZNE format@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}
    The standard .ZNE format is a fairly simple text file to declare
  details of the file.
    You can use this description to write the @{"code" LINK LOAD} you need to
  load the map data into you're programs.
    Here is a line by line summary of the .ZNE format.

  @{B}* The file begins with a remark declaring the file to be ZoneED file.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark naming the date created.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark naming the file and what it's for.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark naming the game/utility it's intended for.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark declaring the author of the zone file.@{UB}
  @{FG FILL}If a background is used to define zones...@{FG TEXT}
    @{B}* the IFF background's full AmigaDOS filename@{UB}
    Finally follows the @{I}zne data.@{UI} It's simply a list of a zone number,
  a starting X co-ord and a Y co-ord and an ending X co-ord and a Y co-ord.

    If a negative number is found this means that it's referring to a new
  zonetable. Blitz has 15 zonetables, each of up to 65550+ zones. Make the
  negative a postive to define which zonetable to use. All the data that 
  follows is intended for that zonetable.
    This means -1 is the first number encountered in the zne file.
  (i.e. Zonetable 1)  

    Rather than waffling on here is an @{"example" LINK XAMPLE} of a zne file.
@ENDNODE

